</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ulunathreee.showPublicProfile?language=EN>lunathreee</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>mistayn the mindless</span><br>  Posts: 404<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/9/02 2:55:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm43.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=122.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How do you set up a Bard gamepad?</span><hr size=1> one inexperienced bardlings view:<br>
<br>
macros<br>
<br>
/stopsong<br>
/cast #<br>
(some pause in here that equates to 3 seconds, because you can't start the next song until the first one is done casting.  i forget what the pause command line is for this.)<br>
/stopsong<br>
/cast #--next song in your lineup, and so on repeat...<br>
<br>
i actually have a strategic commander that has lots of buttons that are completey programmable for almost any computer game you'd wish to play.  i've actually had some trouble with this device &quot;freezin&quot; my keyboard in eq which has resulted in a few deaths, so stopped using it.  too bad, as it's a real wrist-saving device.<br>
<br>
you COULD put a three song twist on one button or one macro, but if you go to the eqdiva site forum, you'll see that this is not viewed as incredibly feasible by the expert bards out there.  <br>
<br>
the reason is:  missed notes.  even the best bards are going to have them, and it's my personal belief that after the advent of Luclin, missed notes (or caster Fizzles)  increased dramatically.  if you miss a note with a macro, your song doesn't start and then you have to wait until the macro is completely done going through its motions to restart.  which means that you're allowing a song or even 3 to possibly drop out of existence altogether.<br>
<br>
so the general advice is, do NOT tie a three song twist to a single key.  it just doesn't allow you to recover in good time.  besides, my personal wisdom is that you may start out the fight by twisting the same three songs, but eventually you're going to want to throw something else into that mix for maximum effectiveness.  <br>
<br>
single song macros are pretty commonly used for each song, with just the /stopsong /cast # commands in them.  no pauses needed, as you're paying attention to the cast bar (and whether the song fizzles on you or not)  to keep your timing correct.  most bards do not seem to use the spellgems/mouse for twisting.<br>
<br>
mine are tied to the numberpad on my keyboard without the /stopsong command.  you can use the Options-Keyboard to set it up so every time you press a number, a spellgem is cast.  i tap the number of the song i'm about to play very briefly to 'stop' the previous song, then hit it again to start the next one.  so my keystrokes equate to:  112233 and so on.<br>
<br>
go here for lots of info on bards<br>
